PERFECT MAHOGANY ROUX: the creole gumbo is delicious and packs some heat.

RAUCOUS VIEUX CARR√â BISTRO: & like the best ones it's loud, congested, & clubby. Desire's sister restaurant, Begue's, was my family and friends' favorite brunch in New Orleans.  And for years it was a well kept secret: $30 for bottomless champagne, an amazing creole buffet and a beautiful dining room over looking the Royal Sonesta's verdant courtyard (this unusual oasis actually has orange trees (!!!) and one drunken Thanksgiving a friend won a bet that they were real by scaling eight feet, in high heels and her best Chanel, to pick one - the little old ladies in hats and familial wait staff gave her a standing O when she alit, prize foisted). But Begue's became a victim of its hubris, raised prices to almost $50, chased off the locals and closed with a whimper.  Thank goodness they didn't ruin Desire!  It's still an earthy Quarter "experience" loved by visitors and locals alike.

A NOLA NATIVE'S RANKING OF FRENCH QUARTER SEAFOOD-ERIES:

1.  GW FINS - only open for dinner so no bargains, but the finest dining alternative;
2.  FELIX'S - better than Acme and no lines; fortuitously it's across the street;
3.  DESIRE - affordable, classic Vieux Carr√© atmosphere, old school wait staff;
4.  RED FISH - Lunch Prix Fixes less than $20, Brennan's quality, healthy choices;
5.  CAF√â SOUL√â - specializes in crab dishes, Antoine's family, classic atmosphere;
6.  DEANIE'S - if you want a menu heavy on fried... uh... everything, huge portions;
7.  MRB - if you can handle bar smoke the oyster & crawfish specials are a deal;
8.  ROYAL HOUSE - best atmosphere, outdoor seating, but touristy & a tad pricey;

DIVIDING LINE BETWEEN BEST & WORST: 9. New Orleans Hamburger & Seafood (a citywide chain; and that should tell you something about the bottom six!)

10.  BOURBON HOUSE - good lunch prix fixe but the oysters are lame;
11.  ACME - our classic oyster bar, but I'm a New Orlenian & don't wait in queue;
12.  OCEANA - nasty dining room, wide but insipid menu, gougingly overpriced;
13.  PIER 424 - ultimate tourist trap on Bourbon, you can do so much better;
14.  RALPH & KACOOS - buses disgorge snowbirds here;
15.  (& Dead Last):  COOP'S - there is absolutely nothing good to be said about it...

DO NOT TOUCH THIS CUP! exclaims the 32oz styrofoam "tip jar" behind the plexi;

SAUCES COST EXTRA, $0.50 each, so all-in the wings here are a so-so deal at $1 per. Also, expect a 3-4 minute wait per order ahead of you, if it's faster it's lagniappe.

I PREFER "VIEUX CARR√â PIZZA'S WINGS" as they are the best "dry" to me.  Simply salt & peppered, sans breading, slowly fire-broiled in a pizza conveyor oven: crispy skin outside, buttery moist inside. AND they don't charge extra for sauces AND it's a less sketchy area (3PM-3AM daily, 733 Toulouse).
